We have gathered here today to consider a number of issues related to the adoption of the new law.

00:24.000 --> 00:27.000
This is the topic of our meeting.

00:27.000 --> 00:30.000
We will start with the definition.

00:30.000 --> 00:33.000
What is meant by the administrative decision?

00:33.000 --> 00:38.000
There are three different things that are meant by the administrative decision.

00:38.000 --> 00:42.000
The first is the choice of the goal.

00:42.000 --> 00:46.000
The second is the path or the direction of the decision.

00:46.000 --> 00:50.000
The third is the process of the decision.

00:50.000 --> 00:55.000
The second is the path or the methods of achieving this goal.

00:55.000 --> 01:01.000
The third is the administrative decision.

01:01.000 --> 01:04.000
Considering the administrative decision as an administrative decision,

01:04.000 --> 01:08.000
we can note two more aspects of this important point.

01:08.000 --> 01:14.000
One of the aspects is the choice of something.

01:14.000 --> 01:22.000
The second is the process of making this choice.

01:22.000 --> 01:26.000
Why is this topic important and simple at the same time?

01:26.000 --> 01:31.000
It is important because the decision-maker is responsible for it.

01:31.000 --> 01:35.000
If the decision is made wrong or ineffective,

01:35.000 --> 01:39.000
someone is subject to sanctions, including the organization.

01:39.000 --> 01:41.000
Why is this topic simple?

01:41.000 --> 01:43.000
We face this issue every day.

01:43.000 --> 01:45.000
We make decisions every day.

01:45.000 --> 01:47.000
What should we cook for breakfast or dinner?

01:47.000 --> 01:49.000
Where should we cross the road?

01:49.000 --> 01:51.000
What traffic light should we cross?

01:51.000 --> 01:53.000
Red or green?

01:53.000 --> 02:00.000
After the general concepts, we will consider the methods of decision-making and classification.

02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
We will consider the new aspects of decision-making.

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
And, of course, psychological issues.

02:08.000 --> 02:11.000
People of different psychotypes make decisions.

02:11.000 --> 02:15.000
We should pay attention to this when working with our colleagues,

02:15.000 --> 02:21.000
superiors, subordinates who make and are responsible for some decisions.

02:21.000 --> 02:25.000
Another term is the person who makes decisions.

02:25.000 --> 02:32.000
It is understood as a manager, that is, the one who leads.

02:32.000 --> 02:37.000
If a person does not make decisions, he is not a manager.

02:37.000 --> 02:40.000
But this is not enough.

02:40.000 --> 02:43.000
To be a manager, you need to have subordinates.

02:43.000 --> 02:47.000
So, the person who makes decisions individually is a manager,

02:47.000 --> 02:49.000
the leader who has subordinates.

02:49.000 --> 02:51.000
And there is another side,

02:51.000 --> 02:54.000
the collective person who makes decisions.

02:54.000 --> 02:57.000
That is, a part of the people, a certain circle,

02:57.000 --> 02:59.000
who make decisions together.

02:59.000 --> 03:03.000
We will discuss the issue of decision-making in a moment.

03:03.000 --> 03:09.000
But for now, let's move on to the concept of right and wrong decisions.

03:09.000 --> 03:13.000
We often come across different examples.

03:13.000 --> 03:17.000
For example, on Tuesday, the president sent the government to resign.

03:17.000 --> 03:19.000
Is this decision right or wrong?

03:19.000 --> 03:21.000
Nobody knows today.

03:21.000 --> 03:28.000
In our course, I hope we will learn to make only right decisions.

03:28.000 --> 03:31.000
I can share that as a professor of famous academies,

03:31.000 --> 03:34.000
who has long read the NIMB and conducted training,

03:34.000 --> 03:37.000
I always make only right decisions.

03:37.000 --> 03:39.000
Why?

03:39.000 --> 03:42.000
We will talk about this later.

03:42.000 --> 03:46.000
So, what and how are decisions made?

03:46.000 --> 03:50.000
In fact, the scheme of decision-making itself is very simple.

03:50.000 --> 03:52.000
This is the problem-solving.

03:52.000 --> 03:54.000
What is it?

03:54.000 --> 03:56.000
And what do we need to solve?

03:56.000 --> 04:01.000
The second stage is, as a rule, the selection of criteria and restrictions

04:01.000 --> 04:03.000
when solving this problem.

04:03.000 --> 04:06.000
The third stage is the development of alternatives,

04:06.000 --> 04:11.000
that is, the different ways in which this problem can be solved.

04:11.000 --> 04:14.000
Then there is a choice of one or two of the ways,

04:14.000 --> 04:18.000
of the set that we have determined.

04:18.000 --> 04:21.000
And the implementation of the solution, of course,

04:21.000 --> 04:24.000
with a feedback to the original problem.

04:24.000 --> 04:29.000
In fact, these stages are broken up in different sources.

04:29.000 --> 04:36.000
There are many of them, and we can look and think,

04:36.000 --> 04:39.000
but the essence of this will not change.

04:39.000 --> 04:44.000
Now let's look at the classification of decision-making.

04:44.000 --> 04:49.000
It also varies in different sources.

04:49.000 --> 04:55.000
First of all, management decisions are usually divided into external and internal.

04:55.000 --> 05:00.000
External decisions affect any changes outside the organization.

05:00.000 --> 05:03.000
For example, the development of new markets,

05:03.000 --> 05:07.000
as an example, the confrontation of competition,

05:07.000 --> 05:11.000
as an example, decisions aimed at, let's say,

05:11.000 --> 05:15.000
absorbing enterprises or creating branches.

05:15.000 --> 05:19.000
There are also internal solutions to internal problems.

05:19.000 --> 05:22.000
These are changes in personnel policy,

05:22.000 --> 05:25.000
changes in the assortment minimum,

05:25.000 --> 05:34.000
changes in the price range due to changes in the costs within the organization.

05:34.000 --> 05:38.000
This is one component of the classification.

05:38.000 --> 05:41.000
It does not affect any other components of the classification.

05:41.000 --> 05:45.000
Accordingly, if we look at the scale,

05:45.000 --> 05:49.000
there are decisions made at the state level,

05:49.000 --> 05:53.000
decisions made at the level of the federation,

05:53.000 --> 05:56.000
they all affect our business and the management of our organization,

05:56.000 --> 05:58.000
the life of the general manager.

05:58.000 --> 06:02.000
Decisions made at the level of municipal education

06:02.000 --> 06:05.000
and decisions made in the organization itself.

06:05.000 --> 06:09.000
These are all management decisions at the hierarchy level,

06:09.000 --> 06:14.000
which affect the life and career of the first line manager,

06:14.000 --> 06:17.000
from which management begins.

06:17.000 --> 06:21.000
Next, management decisions on time,

06:21.000 --> 06:24.000
their development and adoption.

06:24.000 --> 06:27.000
They are usually divided into strategic decisions,

06:27.000 --> 06:31.000
tactical decisions and operational decisions.

06:31.000 --> 06:37.000
Strategic decisions consider a period of at least 3 to 5 years,

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
and are associated with the strategy of the development of the entire organization.

06:40.000 --> 06:46.000
Tactical decisions consider a shorter period of time, up to 3 years,

06:46.000 --> 06:49.000
from one year to three, sometimes from six months.

06:49.000 --> 06:53.000
And operational decisions are those decisions that are made today,

06:53.000 --> 06:55.000
for a week, for a month.

06:55.000 --> 06:59.000
For example, operational decisions.

06:59.000 --> 07:01.000
New Year's Eve.

07:01.000 --> 07:05.000
The whole country celebrates the holidays, including Moscow.

07:05.000 --> 07:08.000
And somewhere in a room on duty,

07:08.000 --> 07:16.000
a brigade of duty plumbers and 3-4 plumber specialists are sitting.

07:16.000 --> 07:18.000
And then a phone call comes in,

07:18.000 --> 07:21.000
that there was an accident on the heat networks.

07:21.000 --> 07:27.000
A huge heat network, a pipe, broke, and water flows out into the street.

07:27.000 --> 07:31.000
It's cold at night, it's winter, people are celebrating.

07:31.000 --> 07:34.000
You need to make a decision for the plumber.

07:34.000 --> 07:39.000
Who should be immediately pulled out of the table and sent to liquidate the breakthrough?

07:39.000 --> 07:42.000
What forces should be used, what services should be additionally attracted?

07:42.000 --> 07:45.000
This is an operational decision, it is already made quickly.

07:45.000 --> 07:49.000
Further, decisions can be formalized,

07:49.000 --> 07:52.000
poorly formalized and not formalized.

07:52.000 --> 07:59.000
Formalized decisions are those decisions that are described using numbers, formulas.

07:59.000 --> 08:07.000
And are easily taken into account when processing on electronic computing.

08:07.000 --> 08:13.000
Examples of such a decision can be the decision to pay for newborns.

08:13.000 --> 08:17.000
Because you can count how many men and women in our country,

08:17.000 --> 08:20.000
how many families, how many women of childbearing age,

08:20.000 --> 08:23.000
and how many women who are able to give birth further.

08:23.000 --> 08:28.000
Count how much money will be spent from the budget

08:28.000 --> 08:35.000
to provide all those women who are able to give birth with material stimulation.

08:35.000 --> 08:38.000
This is a formalized decision that was adopted at the state level.

08:38.000 --> 08:44.000
Poorly formalized decisions have a greater degree of uncertainty.

08:44.000 --> 08:51.000
No one can predict what the price of the dollar will be tomorrow.

08:51.000 --> 08:59.000
Or what consequences of price education on transport services and energy carriers

08:59.000 --> 09:01.000
will cause changes in the government of the Russian Federation,

09:01.000 --> 09:05.000
which we have seen just recently.

09:05.000 --> 09:09.000
There are decisions that are not formalized,

09:10.000 --> 09:14.000
that are not formalized in some kind of electronic computing and calculation.

09:14.000 --> 09:18.000
For example, the decision adopted by the brigade commander

09:18.000 --> 09:22.000
in the example of the New Year's Eve and the repair of the thermal power plant.

09:22.000 --> 09:30.000
Further, management decisions are divided into routine, creative and unique.

09:30.000 --> 09:32.000
What are the differences between them?

09:32.000 --> 09:41.000
Routine decisions are those that are adopted without any creative processes in the head of the person who adopts them.

09:41.000 --> 09:46.000
For example, the order to start the heating season is signed annually in the mayors,

09:46.000 --> 09:52.000
in the administration and in a number of municipal organizations.

09:52.000 --> 09:55.000
What is creative here? Nothing.

09:55.000 --> 09:57.000
The order simply changes the dates,

09:57.000 --> 10:03.000
and the person can start working and start borrowing money for hot water.

10:03.000 --> 10:04.000
That's it.

10:04.000 --> 10:07.000
These are simple routine decisions.

10:07.000 --> 10:13.000
Creative decisions differ in that something new needs to be developed here.

10:13.000 --> 10:20.000
For example, the company's exit to some new markets.

10:20.000 --> 10:22.000
What to go out with?

10:22.000 --> 10:23.000
What product?

10:23.000 --> 10:24.000
Where to start?

10:24.000 --> 10:29.000
To openly present yourself as a branch or to agree with someone on some commercial conditions.

10:29.000 --> 10:32.000
Here you need to think and calculate.

10:32.000 --> 10:38.000
This decision can be both tactical, creative and poorly formalized.

10:38.000 --> 10:44.000
Further, unique decisions are further development of creative decisions,

10:44.000 --> 10:51.000
but they differ in that one such decision makes a turn of the company's life.

10:51.000 --> 10:55.000
For example, this is a classic example, it appears in textbooks.

10:55.000 --> 11:00.000
Once cars were produced in small quantities as luxury.

11:00.000 --> 11:01.000
Just for show.

11:01.000 --> 11:03.000
You just drove a car and that's it.

11:03.000 --> 11:11.000
Once Henry Ford made a unique management decision to start mass production of cars.

11:11.000 --> 11:16.000
Of course, it was unpopular at that time, and no one understood it.

11:16.000 --> 11:18.000
But there were a lot of cars.

11:18.000 --> 11:20.000
There were horses, crews, horses, railways.

11:20.000 --> 11:21.000
Why?

11:21.000 --> 11:25.000
Today we all just can't imagine our lives without cars.

11:25.000 --> 11:30.000
Further, there are both periodic and non-periodic decisions.

11:30.000 --> 11:35.000
Periodic decisions are those that arise constantly with a certain regularity.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.000
For example, the care of summer vacation employees.

11:38.000 --> 11:43.000
Every year you need to decide who to let on vacation, when, and make a schedule.

11:43.000 --> 11:45.000
It's all easy and simple.

11:45.000 --> 11:52.000
There are non-periodic decisions, like changing the price policy due to the change in the price of energy.

11:52.000 --> 11:54.000
We don't know when they will change.

11:54.000 --> 12:04.000
If we have energy-efficient production, we have to react to such non-periodic changes in external indicators

12:04.000 --> 12:07.000
by making appropriate decisions.

12:07.000 --> 12:09.000
What to do and how to get out of it.

12:09.000 --> 12:15.000
There are also periodic and non-periodic decisions.

12:15.000 --> 12:18.000
Periodic decisions are those that need to be made now,

12:18.000 --> 12:27.000
like the decision of the brigade of plumbers and plumbers that we repair and apply.

12:27.000 --> 12:29.000
And non-periodic decisions.

12:29.000 --> 12:34.000
For example, we need to decide what we will do in winter, in preparation for winter vacation.

12:34.000 --> 12:41.000
When children go to school, we could offer our company some food for children going on winter vacation.

12:41.000 --> 12:46.000
We have time to think, calculate, and determine methods of decision-making.

12:46.000 --> 12:53.000
Now, after the classification of decisions, let's look at several examples of such decisions.

12:53.000 --> 12:56.000
Let's try to classify them.

12:56.000 --> 13:01.000
Let's recall a very interesting situation.

13:01.000 --> 13:06.000
Many people have read about the legendary hero of America, Thomas Sawyer.

13:06.000 --> 13:11.000
Once his aunt sent him to paint a fence.

13:11.000 --> 13:13.000
We will come back to this example later.

13:13.000 --> 13:16.000
Thomas Sawyer, having no desire to do it,

13:16.000 --> 13:20.000
he was a normal guy, not eager to paint fences,

13:20.000 --> 13:26.000
came to this fence with a bucket of paint, a brush, and no desire.

13:27.000 --> 13:38.000
He painted it, noticed his friend, and asked him to paint it.

13:38.000 --> 13:43.000
Thomas Sawyer persuaded his friend, convinced him,

13:43.000 --> 13:45.000
and he started painting the fence with pleasure.

13:45.000 --> 13:47.000
Then he passed it on to another friend, the third or fourth friend.

13:47.000 --> 13:50.000
And this is how the process ended.

13:50.000 --> 13:56.000
The paint was used, the fence was painted in three and a half rows,

13:56.000 --> 14:02.000
Thomas Sawyer rested in the shade, ate delicious apples, and started to give a bunch of toys.

14:02.000 --> 14:08.000
The question is, what decision was it, internal or external, for Thomas Sawyer?

14:08.000 --> 14:13.000
On the one hand, it was internal, because he did it for himself,

14:13.000 --> 14:15.000
he did not have an organization.

14:15.000 --> 14:20.000
On the other hand, it was external, because he brought in external resources to solve the problem.

14:20.000 --> 14:23.000
The problem was that the fence had to be painted without any desire.

14:23.000 --> 14:28.000
Next, what level of hierarchy was this decision made at?

14:28.000 --> 14:31.000
It was made at the lower level, at the level of the executor,

14:31.000 --> 14:33.000
that is, at the level of the organization.

14:33.000 --> 14:35.000
We look at it by level.

14:35.000 --> 14:40.000
Next, what was this decision, strategic, tactical, or operational?

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
It was, of course, operational.

14:42.000 --> 14:45.000
He could not expect to be sent to paint the fence in the morning,

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
and on the other hand, having painted the fence,

14:47.000 --> 14:53.000
it had no consequences for him in the future, in his development as a person.

14:53.000 --> 15:00.000
Next, on the formalizability and non-formalizability of this decision.

15:00.000 --> 15:04.000
Of course, the decision was not subject to formalization, it was informal.

15:04.000 --> 15:11.000
Next, on the routine and creativity, it was a creative decision.

15:11.000 --> 15:14.000
On the one hand, there was nothing unique to turn the world upside down,

15:14.000 --> 15:16.000
or Thomas Sawyer's life.

15:16.000 --> 15:20.000
On the other hand, it was new, and he had to think about it.

15:20.000 --> 15:26.000
This decision was not periodic, it occurred by chance, under the influence of external factors.

15:26.000 --> 15:30.000
And, of course, it was urgent.

15:30.000 --> 15:33.000
This is a simple decision.

15:33.000 --> 15:38.000
Now, looking at how decisions are made, how they are implemented,

15:38.000 --> 15:46.000
let's look at three more points, which concern the implementation of management decisions.

15:46.000 --> 15:51.000
Management decisions, of course, are the dream of every manager,

15:51.000 --> 15:55.000
to be decided in the best way possible.

15:55.000 --> 15:57.000
The decision must be optimal.

15:57.000 --> 16:07.000
An optimal decision is when, having chosen some criteria for the second stage of decision making,

16:07.000 --> 16:15.000
we reach the extremum when considering some function.

16:15.000 --> 16:18.000
This is either the maximum or the minimum.

16:18.000 --> 16:20.000
The optimum function exists.

16:20.000 --> 16:22.000
Let's take a simple example.

16:22.000 --> 16:32.000
When the head of the department selects a team.

16:32.000 --> 16:39.000
The department decides to optimize the number of each unit,

16:39.000 --> 16:46.000
when the number of units is determined based on psychological qualities.

16:46.000 --> 16:52.000
Based on psychology, the department decides that the optimal number of units is 8 people,

16:52.000 --> 16:54.000
7 subordinates.

16:54.000 --> 16:55.000
Why?

16:55.000 --> 16:58.000
Because the maximum number of units of information

16:58.000 --> 17:02.000
a normal person in a normal country can keep under control at the same time.

17:02.000 --> 17:03.000
7 people.

17:03.000 --> 17:06.000
Okay, this is an optimal decision.

17:06.000 --> 17:11.000
There is another type of decision.

17:11.000 --> 17:13.000
This is an acceptable decision.

17:13.000 --> 17:16.000
Some parameters do not allow us,

17:16.000 --> 17:18.000
let's say, the room parameters,

17:18.000 --> 17:22.000
the rooms that are determined by the sales department.

17:22.000 --> 17:28.000
Then we can make a group of 6-7 people.

17:28.000 --> 17:30.000
This is an acceptable decision,

17:30.000 --> 17:34.000
because the head will have 5-6 subordinates,

17:34.000 --> 17:36.000
they all get into the attention zone,

17:36.000 --> 17:37.000
into the control zone,

17:37.000 --> 17:39.000
he controls them normally.

17:39.000 --> 17:45.000
But he has one free will,

17:45.000 --> 17:47.000
and he is underprivileged.

17:48.000 --> 17:50.000
But the decision is acceptable,

17:50.000 --> 17:51.000
it is possible,

17:51.000 --> 17:58.000
and the department can cope with the tasks set by the head.

17:58.000 --> 18:04.000
There is also a group of decisions that are called satisfactory.

18:04.000 --> 18:07.000
In the same example,

18:07.000 --> 18:13.000
when we determine the number of sales units for the first line manager,

18:14.000 --> 18:21.000
as a rule, we have a number of subordinates in the country of 3-5 people.

18:23.000 --> 18:24.000
Why?

18:24.000 --> 18:27.000
There are reasons for this, not psychological,

18:27.000 --> 18:29.000
but reasons for professional training,

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
professional skills, knowledge and skills,

18:32.000 --> 18:35.000
and also the intellectual abilities of the head.

18:35.000 --> 18:38.000
As a rule, unfortunately,

18:38.000 --> 18:43.000
our managers hardly keep 6-7 people under control.

18:43.000 --> 18:45.000
3-5 is the norm.

18:45.000 --> 18:48.000
If we consider the structure of many companies,

18:48.000 --> 18:50.000
most of them are like this.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
When we start drawing the management work structure,

18:53.000 --> 18:58.000
we make decisions on the creation of the entire management system of the organization,

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
as a rule, we make small organizations,

19:00.000 --> 19:02.000
25 people, no more.

19:02.000 --> 19:04.000
Because we are building with 25 people,

19:04.000 --> 19:08.000
we learn to find management decisions,

19:08.000 --> 19:12.000
how to distribute duties between departments in the best way.

19:12.000 --> 19:15.000
When we try to take more than 50 people,

19:15.000 --> 19:18.000
70 people, then unfortunately our groups are drowning.

19:18.000 --> 19:20.000
Because of the training.

19:20.000 --> 19:24.000
When a person builds a small organization several times,

19:24.000 --> 19:27.000
it becomes easier for him to build for large ones,

19:27.000 --> 19:31.000
and when he comes to his organization,

19:31.000 --> 19:35.000
based on the skills and skills gained,

19:35.000 --> 19:38.000
it is possible to structure the work of the whole organization.

19:38.000 --> 19:41.000
We have an optimal solution,

19:41.000 --> 19:44.000
if we look at psychology,

19:44.000 --> 19:47.000
that is, 7 subordinates and a manager,

19:47.000 --> 19:49.000
that is, 8 people in the department.

19:49.000 --> 19:52.000
An acceptable solution,

19:52.000 --> 19:57.000
when the number of departments is not equal to 8,

19:57.000 --> 19:59.000
that is, from 6-7 people,

19:59.000 --> 20:01.000
in principle, up to 10.

20:01.000 --> 20:05.000
We can overload our manager with additional duties,

20:05.000 --> 20:06.000
additional people,

20:06.000 --> 20:09.000
with certain intellectual qualities,

20:09.000 --> 20:11.000
and this will be justified economically,

20:11.000 --> 20:12.000
according to the second criterion,

20:12.000 --> 20:13.000
according to another criterion,

20:13.000 --> 20:14.000
the criterion of the economy.

20:14.000 --> 20:19.000
When increasing the number of subordinates for each manager,

20:19.000 --> 20:22.000
we reduce the number of managers in the organization,

20:22.000 --> 20:26.000
and, accordingly, reduce the cost of salary

20:26.000 --> 20:29.000
to the paid managers.

20:29.000 --> 20:31.000
This is beneficial for the organization.

20:31.000 --> 20:33.000
But this is the second criterion.

20:33.000 --> 20:36.000
And according to the same criterion,

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
the psychological composition of the group,

20:38.000 --> 20:43.000
we issue satisfactory solutions,

20:43.000 --> 20:46.000
which simply satisfy the conditions of the organization,

20:46.000 --> 20:51.000
they do not exceed the psychological capabilities of our manager,

20:51.000 --> 20:54.000
and he works quite calmly.

20:55.000 --> 21:01.000
Now let's return to the person making the decision.

21:03.000 --> 21:05.000
As we have already said,

21:05.000 --> 21:06.000
as we know,

21:06.000 --> 21:10.000
the person making the decision can be a single person,

21:10.000 --> 21:12.000
an individual person,

21:12.000 --> 21:17.000
and it can be a collective, collegial person making the decision.

21:17.000 --> 21:19.000
And, accordingly,

21:19.000 --> 21:22.000
before talking about them,

21:22.000 --> 21:27.000
let's briefly consider how decisions are made in the main known models,

21:27.000 --> 21:31.000
the American and Eastern models of management and business.

21:31.000 --> 21:32.000
And, accordingly,

21:32.000 --> 21:34.000
they have their own culture of decision-making,

21:34.000 --> 21:36.000
which is formed by the whole system.

21:36.000 --> 21:40.000
So, in the American model of business management,

21:40.000 --> 21:44.000
each manager of this particular system

21:44.000 --> 21:50.000
personally makes decisions and is responsible for them.

21:50.000 --> 21:56.000
This is the value of this model and the value of this manager.

21:56.000 --> 22:01.000
And, in fact, the value of the mentality of the United States of America.

22:01.000 --> 22:06.000
By the way, the Western model interpreted in the classic management

22:06.000 --> 22:09.000
explains that it is supposedly in the middle

22:09.000 --> 22:12.000
between the American model and the Eastern model.

22:12.000 --> 22:17.000
This is somewhat wrong in my opinion,

22:17.000 --> 22:22.000
because the Western model is a pro-image of the American model.

22:22.000 --> 22:24.000
The American model has grown out of it,

22:24.000 --> 22:27.000
but it has become a little tougher.

22:27.000 --> 22:31.000
The Western model has all the same principles as the American model,

22:31.000 --> 22:34.000
only it is softer, more kind, a little older,

22:34.000 --> 22:36.000
and, accordingly, it has a softer character,

22:36.000 --> 22:38.000
like a person who is older, like a grandmother,

22:38.000 --> 22:41.000
she is much calmer than a 19-year-old lady.

22:41.000 --> 22:42.000
Right?

22:42.000 --> 22:44.000
This is how it is with these models.

22:44.000 --> 22:47.000
The American model is tougher, but all the principles are the same.

22:47.000 --> 22:50.000
In fact, it can be said that in management

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
there are only two models of management,

22:52.000 --> 22:55.000
the American one, where the material is Eastern,

22:55.000 --> 22:58.000
and in them there are corresponding schemes for making decisions.

22:58.000 --> 23:00.000
So we move on.

23:00.000 --> 23:02.000
By the way, why are we moving on to this,

23:02.000 --> 23:05.000
to the consideration of how decisions are made in these models?

23:05.000 --> 23:07.000
Maybe we don't need it?

23:09.000 --> 23:11.000
Maybe we need it for this.

23:11.000 --> 23:15.000
Many companies in our country are now signing contracts with foreign companies.

23:15.000 --> 23:19.000
We went abroad, we communicate with the West, with America, with the East.

23:19.000 --> 23:24.000
The Asian tigers that grow fast came to our country with different offers.

23:24.000 --> 23:29.000
On the one hand, on the other hand, our guys, growing managers,

23:29.000 --> 23:31.000
who are striving to make a career,

23:31.000 --> 23:34.000
often get a job in a foreign company,

23:34.000 --> 23:40.000
both in a Western, pro-American, or purely American, or in an Eastern company.

23:40.000 --> 23:43.000
And of course, to make a career in these companies,

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
you need to know the rules of the game.

23:45.000 --> 23:50.000
So, as we know,

23:50.000 --> 23:55.000
the manager makes decisions in the American model personally,

23:55.000 --> 23:59.000
usually without any responsibility,

23:59.000 --> 24:04.000
often without consulting anyone, to the extent of his authority.

24:04.000 --> 24:07.000
He makes decisions, he is responsible for them.

24:07.000 --> 24:10.000
The decision is made quickly, it is quickly realized,

24:10.000 --> 24:14.000
and this has enabled the rapid growth of the American economy

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
after the creation of the United States of America

24:17.000 --> 24:21.000
and after their transition to the capitalist economy.

24:21.000 --> 24:25.000
After all, America is actually younger than the whole mother Europe,

24:25.000 --> 24:28.000
but it developed quickly and took a leading position.

24:28.000 --> 24:34.000
That is, the entire American economy works better than the entire Western and even Eastern European economies.

24:35.000 --> 24:42.000
The difference between the East and the West is that decisions are made slowly.

24:42.000 --> 24:46.000
Then all decisions are made collectively,

24:46.000 --> 24:51.000
the so-called system of circular visioning.

24:51.000 --> 24:55.000
That is, a group of people is gathered, responsible at some level,

24:55.000 --> 25:01.000
they discuss the problem, find solutions according to the scheme previously discussed,

25:01.000 --> 25:04.000
choose a solution, and then the solution is made.

25:04.000 --> 25:10.000
In fact, while the solutions can be strong, good, and optimal,

25:10.000 --> 25:13.000
no one personally answers for them.

25:13.000 --> 25:17.000
What was the weakness of the Soviet Union,

25:17.000 --> 25:21.000
and what is our model in Russia today,

25:21.000 --> 25:24.000
American, Western or Eastern?

25:24.000 --> 25:26.000
Western.

25:26.000 --> 25:28.000
But the West is not the same.

25:28.000 --> 25:30.000
Then the East remained.

25:30.000 --> 25:32.000
We have an Eastern model.

25:32.000 --> 25:34.000
We have a collegial decision-making,

25:34.000 --> 25:37.000
we have a prime minister who has a cabinet of ministers,

25:37.000 --> 25:40.000
who allegedly participate in decision-making.

25:40.000 --> 25:44.000
We have a collegium of public figures,

25:44.000 --> 25:47.000
heads of sub-departmental organizations,

25:47.000 --> 25:53.000
who also meet periodically to make collegial decisions.

25:53.000 --> 25:55.000
Let's take the simplest question.

25:55.000 --> 25:57.000
Can you do it with my example?

25:57.000 --> 26:00.000
When I was doing my postgraduate studies,

26:00.000 --> 26:04.000
I had to write a document called a characteristic.

26:04.000 --> 26:09.000
It was signed by the head of the department,

26:09.000 --> 26:14.000
the pro-fork department, the port-ork department, and the comm-sork department.

26:14.000 --> 26:16.000
Four people.

26:16.000 --> 26:20.000
After that, I moved from the department to the faculty level,

26:20.000 --> 26:22.000
a little higher, to another level of management.

26:22.000 --> 26:25.000
And there I was signed by the port-ork faculty,

26:25.000 --> 26:31.000
the pro-fork faculty, the comm-sork faculty, and the dean of the faculty.

26:31.000 --> 26:36.000
It seemed that I could be congratulated on my postgraduate studies.

26:36.000 --> 26:39.000
This was the decision of management implementation.

26:39.000 --> 26:42.000
After that, the characteristic went to an even higher level,

26:42.000 --> 26:48.000
to the top level, where it was signed by the chairman of the port-comm,

26:49.000 --> 26:51.000
the vice-chairman of the university's legal committee,

26:51.000 --> 26:54.000
the secretary of the university's committee of the LCCM,

26:54.000 --> 26:57.000
and the rector of the university's higher educational institution.

26:57.000 --> 27:01.000
In total, 12 signatures, plus the signature of the scientific director,

27:01.000 --> 27:04.000
who accepted me, 13.

27:04.000 --> 27:10.000
Any person, any citizen of the Soviet Union in those years,

27:10.000 --> 27:13.000
in order to enter the postgraduate studies,

27:13.000 --> 27:17.000
according to the usual, simple, eastern model of decision-making,

27:17.000 --> 27:22.000
had to have a good, at least, a friendly, comfortable relationship

27:22.000 --> 27:26.000
with any official at any level.

27:26.000 --> 27:31.000
Any un-signed characteristic could slow down the decision-making.

27:31.000 --> 27:34.000
And it would never be implemented.

27:34.000 --> 27:38.000
And no one would be responsible for it.

27:38.000 --> 27:42.000
Here are two models.

27:42.000 --> 27:46.000
A person, choosing a company,

27:46.000 --> 27:48.000
moving to another job,

27:48.000 --> 27:52.000
finishing the MBA course with a master's degree in business administration,

27:52.000 --> 27:57.000
making a decision about the choice of a Western, American or Eastern company,

27:57.000 --> 27:59.000
has to look at himself first.

27:59.000 --> 28:02.000
How do I like to make decisions?

28:02.000 --> 28:03.000
How do I make them?

28:03.000 --> 28:08.000
If I make decisions quickly, personally, and I am ready to answer,

28:08.000 --> 28:12.000
I go to the companies where the model of decision-making is in line.

28:12.000 --> 28:14.000
And it will provide a fast career growth.

28:14.000 --> 28:19.000
Especially having a master's degree in business administration.

28:19.000 --> 28:26.000
If the technique, methodology and the mentality of a researcher

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
of a higher career position

28:30.000 --> 28:33.000
often provides for consultations,

28:33.000 --> 28:38.000
having colleagues, discussing the decision in a hurry,

28:38.000 --> 28:46.000
then you have to choose the company where the decisions are made in a proper way.

28:46.000 --> 28:52.000
Now we can look at another vivid example,

28:52.000 --> 28:57.000
which was developed and published in one of our books,

28:57.000 --> 28:59.000
in Soviet times.

28:59.000 --> 29:06.000
A researcher compared the effectiveness of two decision-making models,

29:06.000 --> 29:11.000
the American model and the Eastern model.

29:11.000 --> 29:16.000
The American model was taken by one of the very tough organizations.

29:16.000 --> 29:21.000
He examined the Italian mafia.

29:21.000 --> 29:24.000
How decisions are made there.

29:24.000 --> 29:30.000
What he noticed was that this work was not allowed to be published,

29:30.000 --> 29:35.000
and only in Russia in the 21st century

29:35.000 --> 29:38.000
some people managed to get into some aspects of this work.

29:38.000 --> 29:40.000
The research was very extensive.

29:40.000 --> 29:47.000
He saw that when a mafia soldier comes to his little boss,

29:47.000 --> 29:52.000
he makes decisions himself,

29:52.000 --> 29:56.000
quickly, without consulting anyone, and answers for himself.

29:56.000 --> 30:00.000
He knows that if he made the wrong decisions,

30:00.000 --> 30:03.000
we are talking about right and wrong decisions again,

30:03.000 --> 30:05.000
then what is his fate?

30:05.000 --> 30:08.000
If his boss finds out about his wrong decision,

30:08.000 --> 30:10.000
then his fate is decided.

30:10.000 --> 30:13.000
The legs are in the cement and the hand is in the river.

30:13.000 --> 30:17.000
All life in this tough system, in the competitive economy,

30:17.000 --> 30:21.000
forced him to make the right decisions.

30:21.000 --> 30:24.000
Those who could not make the right decisions,

30:24.000 --> 30:28.000
quickly stopped being little bosses.

30:28.000 --> 30:30.000
Others took their place.

30:30.000 --> 30:32.000
A natural selection for Darwin.

30:32.000 --> 30:35.000
The strongest wins.

30:35.000 --> 30:40.000
Now, if a question asked to a little boss

30:40.000 --> 30:43.000
goes beyond his competence,

30:43.000 --> 30:45.000
and he has no right to make decisions,

30:45.000 --> 30:50.000
he asks this question to his middle boss.

30:50.000 --> 30:53.000
How does the middle boss make decisions?

30:53.000 --> 31:00.000
Of course, quickly, without consulting anyone,

31:00.000 --> 31:03.000
and answers for himself.

31:03.000 --> 31:09.000
And he knows, like his little subordinate boss,

31:09.000 --> 31:11.000
that if he makes the wrong decisions,

31:11.000 --> 31:14.000
he will quickly stop being a middle boss.

31:14.000 --> 31:17.000
Someone from the little bosses will replace him.

31:18.000 --> 31:20.000
The system is mobile, fast,

31:20.000 --> 31:23.000
and it allows this structure to function well

31:23.000 --> 31:26.000
not only in the competitive economy,

31:26.000 --> 31:30.000
but also in the pressure from the state police.

31:32.000 --> 31:35.000
If a middle boss suddenly meets a question

31:35.000 --> 31:38.000
that he has no right to solve,

31:38.000 --> 31:42.000
he passes it to the boss.

31:42.000 --> 31:45.000
He also makes decisions quickly,

31:45.000 --> 31:48.000
unilaterally, without consulting anyone,

31:48.000 --> 31:50.000
and answers for himself.

31:50.000 --> 31:55.000
He answers for all his property and life,

31:55.000 --> 31:58.000
like all other structural fighters.

31:58.000 --> 32:01.000
Of course, in a market economy,

32:01.000 --> 32:03.000
in a civilized market economy,

32:03.000 --> 32:06.000
people who do not cope with their positions

32:06.000 --> 32:09.000
and make wrong decisions,

32:09.000 --> 32:11.000
usually leave their positions,

32:11.000 --> 32:13.000
as a result of competition for jobs,

32:13.000 --> 32:15.000
but stay alive.

32:15.000 --> 32:18.000
Now, our colleague, the researcher,

32:18.000 --> 32:21.000
compared this rigid structure

32:21.000 --> 32:23.000
that makes decisions according to the American model

32:23.000 --> 32:25.000
to another very rigid structure,

32:25.000 --> 32:28.000
but working in a different style.

32:28.000 --> 32:34.000
This structure was the Central Committee of the LCCM,

32:35.000 --> 32:40.000
the All-Russian Leninist Communist Youth Union.

32:40.000 --> 32:46.000
The general-scale event was being prepared.

32:46.000 --> 32:50.000
This structure, which makes decisions

32:50.000 --> 32:53.000
in the style of the Eastern model,

32:53.000 --> 32:55.000
prepared a document,

32:55.000 --> 32:57.000
where it was written who performs what,

32:57.000 --> 32:59.000
when, what resources are provided for it,

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
and the collection of consent signatures began.

33:02.000 --> 33:06.000
If we need 13 signatures for a simple characteristic,

33:06.000 --> 33:09.000
then for that serious document,

33:09.000 --> 33:12.000
we needed more than 150 signatures.

33:12.000 --> 33:14.000
All signatures were collected,

33:14.000 --> 33:16.000
all signed signatures were positive,

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
no one dared to sign against it,

33:19.000 --> 33:21.000
but the event was not held.

33:21.000 --> 33:23.000
Why were these two examples given?

33:23.000 --> 33:25.000
Not to scold the Eastern model,

33:25.000 --> 33:27.000
it is strong in its own way.

33:27.000 --> 33:29.000
We know that the Japanese, Chinese, Korean,

33:29.000 --> 33:31.000
Singaporean, even Vietnamese management

33:31.000 --> 33:33.000
are very strong.

33:33.000 --> 33:35.000
They are rapidly developing,

33:35.000 --> 33:37.000
but the model is different.

33:37.000 --> 33:40.000
In the model in which the decision-makers

33:40.000 --> 33:42.000
of the LCCM were making,

33:42.000 --> 33:45.000
no one was punished, no one was harmed.

33:45.000 --> 33:47.000
They checked it, and what?

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
It did not work.

33:49.000 --> 33:52.000
Just so we know how decisions are made,

33:52.000 --> 33:56.000
we highlighted these two small aspects.

34:01.000 --> 34:05.000
Having considered the two main models of decision-making,

34:05.000 --> 34:08.000
the two systems of decision-making,

34:08.000 --> 34:10.000
and having considered the example

34:10.000 --> 34:12.000
that characterizes both systems,

34:12.000 --> 34:15.000
let's move on to the qualification

34:15.000 --> 34:17.000
of the manager,

34:17.000 --> 34:20.000
that is, the person making the decision,

34:20.000 --> 34:22.000
to see what decisions

34:22.000 --> 34:24.000
he can make

34:24.000 --> 34:27.000
depending on his qualifications.

34:27.000 --> 34:30.000
The first level, the simplest decisions,

34:30.000 --> 34:32.000
is called the routine level,

34:32.000 --> 34:34.000
where simple decisions are made,

34:34.000 --> 34:36.000
without even requiring a choice.

34:36.000 --> 34:38.000
On the one hand,

34:38.000 --> 34:40.000
we have already briefly mentioned

34:40.000 --> 34:42.000
the classification of decisions.

34:42.000 --> 34:44.000
These are simple decisions

34:44.000 --> 34:46.000
when the situation is known,

34:46.000 --> 34:48.000
repeatable,

34:48.000 --> 34:50.000
and you just need to get it done,

34:50.000 --> 34:52.000
signing an order,

34:52.000 --> 34:54.000
sending a letter, and so on.

34:54.000 --> 34:56.000
There is nothing new here,

34:56.000 --> 34:58.000
it is repeated,

34:58.000 --> 35:00.000
and any novice manager

35:00.000 --> 35:02.000
should be able to cope

35:02.000 --> 35:04.000
with the tasks of this level.

35:04.000 --> 35:06.000
The next level of decision-making

35:06.000 --> 35:08.000
is the selective level.

35:08.000 --> 35:10.000
What is its peculiarity?

35:10.000 --> 35:12.000
The peculiarity is that

35:12.000 --> 35:14.000
the person making the decision

35:14.000 --> 35:16.000
chooses an option

35:16.000 --> 35:18.000
from the number of options

35:18.000 --> 35:20.000
available.

35:20.000 --> 35:22.000
If last year

35:22.000 --> 35:24.000
the task of the person

35:24.000 --> 35:26.000
was to choose

35:26.000 --> 35:28.000
the best option,

35:28.000 --> 35:30.000
if last year

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
the task of reducing costs

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
was solved

35:34.000 --> 35:36.000
by the personnel potential,

35:36.000 --> 35:38.000
if this year

35:38.000 --> 35:40.000
the task was solved

35:40.000 --> 35:42.000
by expanding

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
the assortment of the product line,

35:44.000 --> 35:46.000
if the task was solved

35:46.000 --> 35:48.000
in a different way

35:48.000 --> 35:50.000
last year,

35:50.000 --> 35:52.000
the person recalls

35:52.000 --> 35:54.000
the options

35:54.000 --> 35:56.000
and decides to implement the decision.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
For example, it is not necessary

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
that the person takes care of his personnel.

36:00.000 --> 36:02.000
Maybe it is better to take care of them.

36:02.000 --> 36:04.000
Further,

36:04.000 --> 36:06.000
this is a slightly higher qualification,

36:06.000 --> 36:08.000
the person is able to choose,

36:08.000 --> 36:10.000
the manager is able to choose

36:10.000 --> 36:12.000
something ready.

36:12.000 --> 36:14.000
The next level of skill

36:14.000 --> 36:16.000
is the decision-making

36:16.000 --> 36:18.000
of the adaptation level.

36:18.000 --> 36:20.000
And here

36:20.000 --> 36:22.000
the skill is

36:22.000 --> 36:24.000
that the person,

36:24.000 --> 36:26.000
seeing that

36:26.000 --> 36:28.000
the ready options, decisions

36:28.000 --> 36:30.000
are not related to the optimal

36:30.000 --> 36:32.000
or permissible,

36:32.000 --> 36:34.000
but only satisfactory,

36:34.000 --> 36:36.000
tries to find a new decision.

36:36.000 --> 36:38.000
A decision that will allow

36:38.000 --> 36:40.000
from satisfactory

36:40.000 --> 36:42.000
to the permissible,

36:42.000 --> 36:44.000
and from permissible to the optimal.

36:44.000 --> 36:46.000
That's what it is.

36:46.000 --> 36:48.000
Here

36:48.000 --> 36:50.000
you need to be able

36:50.000 --> 36:52.000
to think creatively

36:52.000 --> 36:54.000
and have a developed creativity

36:54.000 --> 36:56.000
in speaking a psychological language.

36:56.000 --> 36:58.000
To generate new ideas,

36:58.000 --> 37:00.000
new approaches,

37:00.000 --> 37:02.000
and sometimes do what was not done before.

37:02.000 --> 37:04.000
For a simple example,

37:04.000 --> 37:06.000
at the beginning of the summer

37:06.000 --> 37:08.000
I was invited to Rostov.

37:08.000 --> 37:10.000
A colleague came to me

37:10.000 --> 37:12.000
and said that he needed my help.

37:12.000 --> 37:14.000
I came and looked at the situation.

37:14.000 --> 37:16.000
He said that he had never done this before

37:16.000 --> 37:18.000
and could not do it.

37:18.000 --> 37:20.000
I came to make a decision

37:20.000 --> 37:22.000
that had never been done before.

37:22.000 --> 37:24.000
If you had found it without me,

37:24.000 --> 37:26.000
you would have done it yourself.

37:26.000 --> 37:28.000
So we did what was offered.

37:28.000 --> 37:30.000
A new decision that had never been

37:30.000 --> 37:32.000
made in that organization before.

37:32.000 --> 37:34.000
And even higher,

37:34.000 --> 37:36.000
the highest in the qualification

37:36.000 --> 37:38.000
of the decision-making level

37:38.000 --> 37:40.000
is the innovative decision.

37:40.000 --> 37:42.000
Here,

37:42.000 --> 37:44.000
as in the example

37:44.000 --> 37:46.000
with Henry Ford,

37:46.000 --> 37:48.000
you need to find something new,

37:48.000 --> 37:50.000
often unique,

37:50.000 --> 37:52.000
that gives a boost.

37:52.000 --> 37:54.000
If these innovative decisions

37:54.000 --> 37:56.000
were made rarely,

37:56.000 --> 37:58.000
we would probably still be in the wild.

37:58.000 --> 38:00.000
Such decisions were made

38:00.000 --> 38:02.000
to create mobile phones.

38:02.000 --> 38:04.000
Many years ago,

38:04.000 --> 38:06.000
working at a high pace,

38:06.000 --> 38:08.000
going somewhere,

38:08.000 --> 38:10.000
being late for a meeting,

38:10.000 --> 38:12.000
I would call,

38:12.000 --> 38:14.000
I would call and warn

38:14.000 --> 38:16.000
or ask to postpone a meeting.

38:16.000 --> 38:18.000
Now every schoolchild

38:18.000 --> 38:20.000
uses this.

38:20.000 --> 38:22.000
Someone once made a decision

38:22.000 --> 38:24.000
to create a new product.

38:24.000 --> 38:26.000
Once, in Japan,

38:26.000 --> 38:28.000
in the eastern model,

38:28.000 --> 38:30.000
which was criticized

38:30.000 --> 38:32.000
for making decisions,

38:32.000 --> 38:34.000
one of the managers

38:34.000 --> 38:36.000
made a decision

38:36.000 --> 38:38.000
to release audio players.

38:38.000 --> 38:40.000
Many did not believe

38:40.000 --> 38:42.000
that it would be successful,

38:42.000 --> 38:44.000
and we are using them successfully.

